               <p>JOHN SCARLET. I live in <placeName id="t18310630-230-crimeloc1213">New North-street, Red Lionsquare</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310630-230-crimeloc1213" type="placeName" value="New North-street, Red Lionsquare"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310630-230-crimeloc1213" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310630-230-off1211 t18310630-230-crimeloc1213"></join> - the prisoner's mother keeps the house; I occupy two rooms. I went out at nine o'clock in the morning, returned about four or five, and missed this property out of a drawer, which was not locked - the prisoner's father drives the Oxford coach.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310630-230-person1717">
                  ELIZA 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18310630-230-person1717" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310630-230-person1717" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310630-230-person1717" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Middle-row, Holborn, at Mr. Bell's, the pastry-cook - I have known the prisoner nine months, by his coming backwards and forwards. On the 19th of June he brought me a bundle, and asked me to take care of it: I put it into my bed-room - his father and a young man came and fetched it afterwards.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310630-230-person1718">
                  JOSEPH 
                  CHRISTOPHER HATTON
               <interp inst="t18310630-230-person1718" type="surname" value="CHRISTOPHER HATTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310630-230-person1718" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310630-230-person1718" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an apprentice to Messrs. Owen and Williams. The prisoner told me he had left a bundle at Smith's, containing some linen of his own - I did not then know of this loss; I went with his father to Bell's, and brought it away to his mother's - this waistcoat was in it.</p>
               <p>GEORGE PALMER. I am a Policeman. I apprehended<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183106300112"></xptr>the prisoner on the 31st of May - I received this waistcoat from Adams - the prisoner acknowledge that it was Mr. Scarlet's, and said he had lost the handkerchief.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
